Troubleshooting. Networking failures.

The most common ticket is, a service is unreachable from a pod. Use a three question flowchart.

One. Does dee-en-ess resolve. From inside a test pod, n-s-lookup the service. If no, the problem is core-d-en-ess, or the pod's d-n-s policy or resolver config.

Two. Is the service backed by endpoints. Kubectl get endpoints. If it shows none, your selector is wrong, or the pods are not ready. Kubectl describe service shows the selector.

Three. Can the pod reach the port. From a test pod, use n-c. If no, you are looking at a network policy, or a container network interface issue.

Some other common cases. Right service, wrong pod, usually means two services with overlapping selectors, or session affinity that is wrong for your protocol. External traffic not arriving, usually means a load balancer's external address is still pending, because the controller has not provisioned it, or an ingress with an empty address, because the controller is not watching this ingress class. A network policy not blocking, usually means the wrong plugin, because kind-net does not enforce, no policy selects the pods, so they fall back to allow all, or the from and to are too permissive, so re-read the or list and and fields rule. And connection refused from outside, walk the layers. Is the node address reachable. Is the node port open. Does the selector match pods. Are the pods listening on the right port. And does the container port equal the target port.

And the classic debug move. Kubectl run, with the netshoot image, interactive. Netshoot ships every networking tool you can think of. Dig, tcp-dump, m-t-r, curl, n-c, ess-ess, and eye-pee. From inside it, you can prod the cluster the way a misbehaving pod would. On our map, this frames the networking box. Where the three communication paths from notebook nine meet real world breakage, one layer at a time.
